The article is about the proclamation by President Joseph R. Biden Jr. declaring March 2022 as American Red Cross Month. The American Red Cross has a long history of providing aid and support to those in need. The organization, founded in 1881 by Clara Barton, aims to prevent and alleviate human suffering. The Red Cross relies heavily on volunteers, with over 90% of its workers being volunteers. They contribute by donating blood, providing emergency shelter, supporting service members and veterans, and offering medical care and resources to combat diseases globally. During American Red Cross Month, people are encouraged to donate blood and assist communities in need. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of caring for one another and highlights the duty of compassion that we owe to each other. The article concludes with a call to observe the month with appropriate programs, ceremonies, and activities, as well as supporting the work of service and relief organizations.